To calculate the base rate I made a simple Markov chain using data from the last three months.  Assuming that recent trends continue gives the probabilities 0%, 27% and 73% respectively.  However, as the price of bitcoin has been unusually stable over the last several months I adjusted it slightly to acount for this.  That leaves us with the probabilities seen above. My code to build and simulate the Markov chain in R.
```
data <- read.csv("Bitcoin USD historical price.csv")
data$mean <- (data$high + data$low)/2 recent_data <- data[1:60,] plot(data$timestamp, data$mean) p <- mean(-diff(recent_data$mean))
varience <- var(-diff(recent_data$mean))
sd <- sqrt(varience) sim <- function(days, start_price, mean_change, sd) {
  change <- rnorm(mean = mean_change, sd = sd, n = days)
  markov <- cumsum(change)
  markov + start_price
} below_count <- 0
above_count <- 0
N <- 500000
for (i in 1:N) {
  data <- sim(94, 54772, mean = p, sd = sd)
  if (max(data) >= 100000) {
    above_count <- above_count + 1
  }
  if (min(data) <= 25000) {
    below_count <- below_count + 1
  }
} below_count / N
above_count / N
```
